{"body":"**<sub><sub>![P1 Badge](https://img.shields.io/badge/P1-orange?style=flat)</sub></sub>  Anchor sidecar writes to canonical skills root**

The confinement check is anchored to `canonicalize(skill_dir)`, so if `<data_dir>/skills/<name>` is itself a symlink (for example, pre-created on disk), `canonical_base` resolves outside the personal skills tree and the subsequent `starts_with` check still succeeds. In that case, `write_skill_files` can write arbitrary files outside `<data_dir>/skills/<name>` despite the safety guarantee. Please reject symlinked skill roots (or validate against canonical `<data_dir>/skills` plus `<name>` as a normal directory) before accepting writes.

Useful? React with 👍 / 👎.","created_at":"2026-03-11T21:28:09Z","line":525,"path":"crates/tools/src/skill_tools.rs"}
{"body":"**Audit log failures silently swallowed**

The entire I/O closure result is discarded with `let _ = ...`. If the log directory cannot be created or the file cannot be opened/written (e.g., read-only filesystem, disk full, permissions issue), the operation succeeds and there is zero indication that the audit entry was never recorded. For a feature whose safety story explicitly relies on an audit trail (`security-audit.jsonl`), silent failure is a meaningful gap.

At minimum, a `tracing::warn!` on failure would make this observable in logs without failing the write operation itself:

```rust
if let Err(err) = (|| -> std::io::Result<()> {
    std::fs::create_dir_all(&dir)?;
    let mut file = std::fs::OpenOptions::new()
        .create(true)
        .append(true)
        .open(path)?;
    use std::io::Write as _;
    writeln!(file, "{line}")?;
    Ok(())
})() {
    tracing::warn!(
        error = %err,
        skill = skill_name,
        "failed to write sidecar-file audit entry"
    );
}
```","created_at":"2026-03-11T21:29:28Z","line":606,"path":"crates/tools/src/skill_tools.rs"}
{"body":"**`maxItems` limit not reflected in the JSON schema**

`MAX_SIDECAR_FILES_PER_CALL = 16` is enforced server-side in `validate_sidecar_files`, but the `parameters_schema()` `files` array does not declare `"maxItems": 16`. The LLM agent uses this schema to understand what it can send, so it has no advance knowledge of the cap and can only discover it through a runtime error after investing tokens in a too-large call.

Adding `"maxItems"` (and `"minItems": 1`) to the schema surface both constraints to the model upfront:

```rust
"files": {
    "type": "array",
    "description": "Supplementary text files to write inside the skill directory",
    "minItems": 1,
    "maxItems": 16,
    "items": { ... }
}
```","created_at":"2026-03-11T21:29:29Z","line":351,"path":"crates/tools/src/skill_tools.rs"}
{"body":"**No rollback for partially-written batches**

Files are written one-by-one with an atomic rename per file, but the loop has no rollback mechanism. If writing fails mid-batch (e.g., a symlink escape is detected on file 3 of 5, or a directory collision is found on file 4), all previously written files remain on disk. The function returns an error, but the skill directory is now in a partially-updated state that neither the agent nor the user is explicitly told about.

For example, the error path for the symlink check at line 535 returns after `create_dir_all(parent)` has already succeeded for the current file, and after any preceding files in `files[0..i-1]` have been fully written.

This does not affect correctness for the happy path, but it is worth documenting as a known limitation (e.g., in the tool description or docs), or addressed by collecting a list of written paths and removing them in the error branch.","created_at":"2026-03-11T21:29:30Z","line":570,"path":"crates/tools/src/skill_tools.rs"}
{"body":"**<sub><sub>![P2 Badge](https://img.shields.io/badge/P2-yellow?style=flat)</sub></sub>  Validate canonical parent before creating directories**

`write_sidecar_files` calls `create_dir_all(parent)` before checking whether `parent` canonicalizes under the skill root, so a symlinked intermediate path can still cause out-of-tree directory creation even when the write is rejected. For example, if `skills/<name>/link` is a symlink to another location, a request for `link/newdir/file.txt` will create `newdir` at the symlink target before the `starts_with` guard fails. This breaks the confinement guarantee for side effects and should be prevented by validating path ancestry before creating directories.

Useful? React with 👍 / 👎.","created_at":"2026-03-12T11:26:14Z","line":534,"path":"crates/tools/src/skill_tools.rs"}

